        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="ZTo7x9SVbxKRHvP0MKYn-19" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;align=center;verticalAlign=middle;rounded=0;" value="Controller creates the correct enrollment" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="30" width="60" x="587.5" y="416" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="ZTo7x9SVbxKRHvP0MKYn-20" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" value="&lt;h1 style=&quot;margin-top: 0px;&quot;&gt;Discussions&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;p&gt;In this situation if the university wanted to create a &quot;waitlist&quot; feature to the system, the process would look like following. First the course class needs to be modified to change the isFull() logic and add an attribute waitlistCapacity(). This in turn creates a ripple effect as now when the registration controlle checks if the course is full, it needs to handle the data from the waitList instead of just reading a boolean value. There is some ripple effect but depending on the architecture it could be much worse. For example if the registratioController was accessing course.currentEnrollment value directly, instead of using the isFull() method, the creation process for the waitlist would be more difficult&#39;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So in conclusion: By having the logic inside the course class, and using methods rather than public attributes, the ripple effect is reduced making the system easier to expand and iterate further, which in turn increases maintainability&lt;/p&gt;" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="220" width="850" x="100" y="920" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="ZTo7x9SVbxKRHvP0MKYn-22" parent="1" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;strokeColor=none;fillColor=none;align=center;verticalAlign=middle;rounded=0;" value="Classes" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry height="30" width="60" x="130" y="230" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
      </root>
    </mxGraphModel>
  </diagram>
